	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>The Spanish tuna industry is invited to invest in PNG</h1>

			
			<h4>
												12 May 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In an interview with ATUNA, the chief negotiator of the Papua New Guinea (PNG) delegation said in talks with the EU that there was no possibility that the IEPA between the EU and PNG, disputed by the Spanish tuna canners from ANFACO, will be blocked.</p><p>ATUNA highlights the fact that Spanish tuna canners fear that the deal will result in substantially lower prices for canned tuna from PNG. Apart from lower labour costs in PNG, the Spanish fear the future use of cheap illegal, unreported and unregulated tuna as raw material. ANFACO considers this a form of unfair price competition within the European market.</p><p>But the PNG chief negotiator rejects these arguments, pointing out that PNG is considered to be a high-cost country: ‘Labour costs are lower, but we lack any economies of scale in canneries, packaging and services. Our shipping costs of the product are high; and so are the prices of utilities like water and electricity.’ He also denies that PNG will ‘turn into an important “white washing” of cheaper, illegally caught tuna from the Western and Central Pacific’, as advanced by ANFACO. ‘On our own cost, we have started a monitoring system with satellites and observers on board of every vessel. This system is stronger than what is required. And the process is managed through the Western and Central Pacific Fisheries Convention (WCPFC), in which the EU actually is a member. So it is in the hands of the EU. And besides: it is in our own best interest not to [lose] the only commodity we have.’</p><p>According to him, PNG is not interested in fishing for more tuna, but intends to redirect part of the resources to its own newly built industry. ‘We have to grow up economically and try to get independent of donor funding by creating our own industry. It is all about diversification of our economy. We need the Europeans to help us. It is absolutely critical that European investors will come to our country. Actually we would like to encourage Spanish industry to invest in PNG.’</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
Breaking news, ‘No way for Spanish tuna industry to block EU–PNG agreement’, American Albacore.com, quoting <i>ATUNA</i>, 4 March 2011<br />http://www.americanalbacore.com/category/breaking-newshttp://www.americanalbacore.com/category/breaking-news</p><p>Breaking news, ‘No way for Spanish tuna industry to block EU–PNG agreement’, <i>American Albacore.com</i>, quoting <i>ATUNA</i>, 4 March 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.americanalbacore.com/category/breaking-newshttp:/www.americanalbacore.com/category/breaking-news" target="_self">http://www.americanalbacore.com/category/breaking-newshttp://www.america...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The situation of the IEPA between the EU and PNG emphasises that ‘coherence for development’ needs to be improved, in order to ensure that the combined impacts of EU policies – market access, SPS and IUU regulations, fisheries operations, investments, development aid – promote environmentally, socially and economically sustainable fisheries in PNG and the Pacific region. In particular, European private investments in the sustainable development of Pacific-island fisheries could be promoted through the negotiations for a full EPA so as to ensure that both parties’ concerns are met.</p>
		</div>
		
